 Arctic]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Subregion of Asia}}\n{{Infobox continent\n|title               = North Asia\n|image               = North Asia (orthographic projection).svg\n|area                = {{convert|13,100,000|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n|population          = 33,765,005 (2017)\n|density             = 2.6 per km<sup>2</sup>\n|GDP_nominal         = [[USD|$]]300 billion (2017)<ref>[http://mrd.gks.ru/wps/wcm/connect/rosstat_ts/mrd/ru/statistics/grp/ \u0412\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u0440\u0435\u0433\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0443\u043a\u0442::\u041c\u043e\u0440\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0438\u044f\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442]</ref>\n|GDP_PPP             = \n|GDP_per_capita      = [[USD|$]]9,000 (2017)\n|HDI                 = \n|ethnic_groups       = [[Slavs|Slavic]], [[Aleut]], [[Eskimo]], [[Mongols]], [[Turkic peoples|Turkic]], [[Tungusic peoples|Tungusic]], [[Baltic Finnic peoples|Finnic]], [[Samoyedic peoples|Samoyedic]], [[Yukaghirs]] and [[Yeniseian people|Yeniseian]] \n|religions           = [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Orthodox Christianity]], [[Islam]], [[Shamanism]], [[Tengrism]], [[Buddhism]], [[Animism]]\n|demonym             = North Asian<br/>Severoaziatskiy <small>(ru)</small>\n|countries           = {{flag|Russia}}\n|list_countries      = \n|dependencies        = \n|unrecognized        = \n|languages           = {{collapsible list | title = Official languages | [[Russian language|Russian]]}}{{collapsible list | title = Other languages | titlestyle = text-align:left;padding-right:4em;font-weight:normal;background-color:white; | bullets = true | [[Ainu languages|Ainu]] | [[Chukotko-Kamchatkan languages|Chukotko-Kamchatkan]] | [[Eskimo\u2013Aleut languages|Eskimo\u2013Aleut]] | [[Mongolic languages|Mongolic]] | [[Tungusic languages|Tungusic]] | [[Turkic languages|Turkic]] | [[Uralic languages|Uralic]] | [[Yeniseian languages|Yeniseian]] | [[Yukaghir languages|Yukaghir]] | ''Others''}}\n|time                = {{collapsible list | title = 8 time zones | titlestyle = text-align:left;padding-right:4em;font-weight:normal;background-color:white; | bullets = true | [[UTC+05:00|UTC+5]] / [[Yekaterinburg Time|MSK+2]] | [[UTC+06:00|UTC+6]] / [[Omsk Time|MSK+3]] | [[UTC+07:00|UTC+7]] / [[Krasnoyarsk Time|MSK+4]] | [[UTC+08:00|UTC+8]] / [[Irkutsk Time|MSK+5]] | [[UTC+09:00|UTC+9]] / [[Yakutsk Time|MSK+6]] | [[UTC+10:00|UTC+10]] / [[Vladivostok Time|MSK+7]] | [[UTC+11:00|UTC+11]] / [[Srednekolymsk Time|MSK+8]] | [[UTC+12:00|UTC+12]] / [[Kamchatka Time|MSK+9]]}}\n|internet            = [[.ru]]\n|calling_code        = [[List of country calling codes|Zone 7]]\n|cities              = {{collapsible list | title = List | titlestyle = text-align:left;padding-right:4em;font-weight:normal;background-color:white; | bullets = true | [[Barnaul]] | [[Chelyabinsk]] | [[Irkutsk]] | [[Kemerovo]] | [[Khabarovsk]] | [[Krasnoyarsk]] | [[Novokuznetsk]] | [[Novosibirsk]] (largest) | [[Omsk]] | [[Tomsk]] | [[Tyumen]] | [[Vladivostok]] | [[Yakutsk]] | [[Yekaterinburg]]}}\n|m49                 = <code>151</code> \u2013 [[Eastern Europe]]<br /><code>150</code> \u2013 [[Europe]]<br /><code>001</code> \u2013 [[World]]\n|footnotes           = \n}}\n{{Chinese\n|rus=\u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0410\u0437\u0438\u044f\n|rusr=Severnaya Aziya\n}}\n\n'''North Asia''' or '''Northern Asia''' ({{lang-ru|\u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0410\u0437\u0438\u044f|lit=Severnaya Aziya|translit=}}), sometimes also referred to as ''[[Siberia]]'', is a [[subregion|sub-region]] of [[Asia]], consisting of the [[Russia]]n regions east of the [[Ural Mountains]]: '''[[Ural (region)|Ural]],''' '''[[Siberia]]''' and the '''[[Russian Far East]]'''. The region is sometimes also known as '''Asian Russia''' (as opposed to the smaller but more densely populated [[European Russia]] to the west). North Asia is bordered to the north by the [[Arctic Ocean]], to the west by [[Eastern Europe]], to the south by [[Central Asia|Central]] and [[East Asia]] and to the east by the [[Pacific Ocean]] and [[North America]]. North Asia covers an area of approximately {{Convert|13,100,000|km2|sqmi}} or 8.8% of the [[Earth|earth's]] land area, or 1.5 times the size of [[Brazil]]. It is the largest subregion of Asia by area, but is also the least populated, with an approximate total population of only 33 million people or 0.74% of Asia's population. North Asia is solely administrated by Russia, and makes up more than 75% of the territory of the country, but only 22% of its population, at a density of 2.5 people per km<sup>2</sup> (6.5 per sq mi).<ref name=\"Vishnevsky\">{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/esa/population/publications/popdecline/vishnevsky.pdf|title=Replacement Migration: Is it a solution for Russia?|last=Vishnevsky|first=Anatoly|date=15 August 2000|publisher=United Nations Population Division, Department of Economic and Social Affairs|pages=6, 10|accessdate=2008-01-14|work=EXPERT GROUP MEETING ON POLICY RESPONSES TO POPULATION AGEING AND POPULATION DECLINE /UN/POP/PRA/2000/14}}</ref> The region of [[Western Siberia]] and occasionally [[Kazakhstan]] is usually called '''Northwestern Asia''' or '''Northwest Asia''' ({{lang-ru|\u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043e-\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0410\u0437\u0438\u044f|lit=Severo-zapadnaya Aziya}}), although the name sometimes refers to [[Caucasus]] or nearby provinces.\n\nTopographically, the region is dominated by the [[Eurasian Plate]], except for its eastern part, which lies on the [[North American Plate|North American]], [[Amurian Plate|Amurian]] and [[Okhotsk Plate]]s. It is divided by three major plains: the [[West Siberian Plain]], [[Central Siberian Plateau]] and Verhoyansk-Chukotka collision zone. The [[Uralian orogeny]] in the west raised [[Ural Mountains]], the informal boundary between [[Europe]] and Asia. Tectonic and volcanic activities are frequently occurred in the eastern part of the region as part of the [[Ring of Fire]], evidenced by the formation of [[island arc]] such as [[Kuril Islands]] and ultra-prominent peaks such as [[Klyuchevskaya Sopka]], [[Kronotsky]] and [[Koryaksky]]. The central part of North Asia is a [[large igneous province]] called the [[Siberian Traps]], formed by a massive eruption occurred 250 million years ago. The formation of the traps coincided with the [[Permian\u2013Triassic extinction event]].\n\n[[Culture of Europe|European influences]], especially [[Russian culture|Russian]], are strong in the southwestern and central part of the region, due to its high [[Russians|Russian]] population from [[Eastern Europe]] which began to settle the area in the 18th-century CE.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=YKPaLi1d1O4C&printsec=frontcover&dq=russian+culture+in+north+asia#v=onepage&q=russian%20culture&f=false|title=Siberia: A Cultural History|last=Haywood|first=A. J.|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780199754182|language=en}}</ref> The southeastern part is historically under the influence of [[East Asian cultural sphere]], especially the [[Chinese culture|Chinese]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=UfPqBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA269&dq=russian+culture+in+north+asia#v=snippet&q=russian%20culture&f=false|title=Rediscovering Russia in Asia: Siberia and the Russian Far East: Siberia and the Russian Far East|last=Kotkin|first=Stephen|last2=Wolff|first2=David|date=2015-03-04|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781317461302|language=en}}</ref> Indigenous cultures are mostly strong in the eastern and southern part of the region due to concentrated population of indigenous ethnicities.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=tkcqDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=siberia+indigenous+culture#v=onepage&q=indigenous%20culture&f=false|title=Living with Koryak Traditions: Playing with Culture in Siberia|last=King|first=Alexander David|date=2011-06-01|publisher=U of Nebraska Press|isbn=978-0803235090|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=oZCOAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA140&dq=siberia+turkic+culture#v=onepage&q=indigenous%20culture&f=false|title=Ethnic Groups of North, East, and Central Asia: An Encyclopedia|last=Minahan|first=James B.|date=2014-02-10|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=9781610690188|language=en}}</ref> In recent years there are growing number of movements by the indigenous peoples of the region to preserve its culture from extinction.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ZlhuDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA4&dq=siberia+indigenous+culture#v=onepage&q=indigenous%20culture&f=false|title=Siberian Survival: The Nenets and Their Story|last=Golovnev|first=Andrei V.|last2=Osherenko|first2=Gail|date=2018-09-05|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=9781501727221|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=5GRWgX2xQMEC&printsec=frontcover&dq=russia+indigenous+culture+movement#v=onepage&q=russia%20indigenous%20culture%20movement&f=false|title=The Predicament of Chukotka's Indigenous Movement: Post-Soviet Activism in the Russian Far North|last=Gray|first=Patty A.|last2=Gray|first2=Patty|date=2005|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521823463|language=en}}</ref> The region is the home of different peoples such as [[Turkic peoples|Turkic]], [[Tungusic peoples|Tungusic]] and [[Baltic Finnic peoples|Finnic peoples]].\n\n== History ==\n{{Further|History of human settlement in the Ural Mountains|History of Siberia|Outer Manchuria}}\n[[File:Collier's new encyclopedia - a loose-leaf and self-revising reference work with 515 illustrations and ninety-six maps (1921) (14781887444).jpg|thumb|Map of Northern Asia in 1921]]\nThe region was first populated by [[Hominini|hominins]] in the [[Late Pleistocene]], approximately 100,000 years ago,<ref name=\"Slon\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Slon V, Viola B, Renaud G, Gansauge M, Benazzi S, Sawyer S, Hublin J, Shunkov MV, Derevianko AP, Kelso J, Pr\u00fcfer K, Meyer M, P\u00e4\u00e4bo S | title = A fourth Denisovan individual | journal = Science Advances | volume = 3 | issue = 7 | pages = e1700186 | date = July 2017 | pmid = 28695206 | pmc = 5501502 | doi = 10.1126/sciadv.1700186 }}</ref> and modern humans are confirmed to arrived in the region by 45,000 years ago<ref name=\"SciAm\">{{cite web| url=http://www.scientificamerican.com/article/45-000-year-old-mans-genome-sequenced/ |title= 45,000-Year-Old Man's Genome Sequenced| author= Callaway, Ewen & Nature magazine |website=Scientific American |date= 23 October 2014|accessdate= 24 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=October 23, 2014 |title= Genome sequence of a 45,000-year-old modern human from western Siberia |journal=Nature |volume=514 |issue= 7523 |pages= 445\u201349 |doi= 10.1038/nature13810 |pmid=25341783 |pmc=4753769 |last1=Fu |first1=Q |last2=Li |first2=H |last3=Moorjani |first3=P |last4=Jay |first4=F |last5=Slepchenko |first5=SM |last6=Bondarev |first6=AA |last7=Johnson |first7=PL |last8=Aximu-Petri |first8=A |last9=Pr\u00fcfer |first9=K |last10=de Filippo |first10=C |last11=Meyer |first11=M |last12=Zwyns |first12=N |last13=Salazar-Garc\u00eda |first13=DC |last14=Kuzmin |first14=YV |last15=Keates |first15=SG |last16=Kosintsev |first16=PA |last17=Razhev |first17=DI |last18=Richards |first18=MP |last19=Peristov |first19=NV |last20=Lachmann |first20=M |last21=Douka |first21=K |last22=Higham |first22=TF |last23=Slatkin |first23=M |last24=Hublin |first24=JJ |last25=Reich |first25=D |last26=Kelso |first26=J |last27=Viola |first27=TB |last28=P\u00e4\u00e4bo |first28=S |bibcode= 2014Natur.514..445F}}</ref> with the first humans in the region having West Eurasian origins.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=K\u0131l\u0131n\u00e7|first=G\u00fcl\u015fah Merve|last2=Kashuba|first2=Natalija|last3=Yaka|first3=Reyhan|last4=S\u00fcmer|first4=Arev Pelin|last5=Y\u00fcnc\u00fc|first5=Eren|last6=Shergin|first6=Dmitrij|last7=Ivanov|first7=Grigorij Leonidovich|last8=Kichigin|first8=Dmitrii|last9=Pestereva|first9=Kjunnej|date=2018-06-12|title=Investigating Holocene human population history in North Asia using ancient mitogenomes|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=8|issue=1|pages=8969|doi=10.1038/s41598-018-27325-0|issn=2045-2322|pmc=5997703|pmid=29895902|bibcode=2018NatSR...8.8969K}}</ref> Its [[Neolithic]] culture is characterized by characteristic stone production techniques and the presence of pottery of eastern origin.<ref name=\":0\" /> The [[Bronze Age]] began during the 3rd millennium BCE,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dupuy|first=Paula Doumani|date=2016-06-02|title=Bronze Age Central Asia|url=http://www.oxfordhandbooks.com/view/10.1093/oxfordhb/9780199935413.001.0001/oxfordhb-9780199935413-e-15|language=en|doi=10.1093/oxfordhb/9780199935413.001.0001|doi-broken-date=2020-01-22}}</ref> with influences of [[Indo-Iranians|Indo-Iranian]] cultures as evidenced by the [[Andronovo culture]]. During the 1st millennium BCE, [[Polity|polities]] such as the [[Scythians]] and [[Xiongnu]]s emerged in the region, who often clashed with its [[List of Iranian dynasties and countries|Persian]] and [[Dynasties in Chinese history|Chinese]] neighbors in the south. The [[Turkic Khaganate]] dominated southern Siberia during the 1st millennium CE, while in the early 2nd millennium CE, the [[Mongol Empire]] and its [[Division of the Mongol Empire|successor states]] ruled the region. The [[Khanate of Sibir]] was one of the last independent [[Turkic peoples|Turkic]] states in North Asia before its [[Conquest of the Khanate of Sibir|conquest]] by the [[Tsardom of Russia]] in the 16th century CE. Russia would then gradually incorporate the region into its territory until the [[Convention of Peking]] was signed in 1860. After the [[October Revolution]] in 1917, the region was [[Eastern Front of the Russian Civil War|contested]] between the Bolsheviks and Whites until the [[Soviet Union]] asserted full control in 1923. The collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991 left Russia as the administrator of the region.\n\n== Geography ==\n{{further|Geography of Siberia|Geography of Russia#Northeast Siberia and Kamchatka}}\nFor geographic and statistical reasons, the [[UN geoscheme]] and various other classification schemes will not subdivide countries, and thus place all of Russia in the [[Europe]] or [[Eastern Europe]] subregion.\n\nThere are no mountain chains in Northern Asia to prevent air currents from the [[Arctic]] flowing down over the [[plain]]s of [[Siberia]] and [[Turkestan]].<ref name=\"Chambers\">{{cite book|title=Chambers's Information for the People|url=https://archive.org/details/chamberssinform02chamgoog|author=William Chambers and Robert Chambers|publisher=W. &amp; R. Chambers|year=1875|location=London and Edinburgh|pages=274\u2013276}}</ref>\n\nThe [[plateau]] and plains of Northern Asia comprise the [[West Siberian plain|West Siberian lowlands]]; the [[Angara Shield]], with the [[Taimyr Peninsula]], the coastal lowlands ([[North Siberian Lowland]] and [[East Siberian Lowland]]), the [[Central Siberian Plateau]], ([[Putorana Plateau]], [[Lena Plateau]], [[Anabar Plateau]], [[Tunguska Plateau]], [[Vilyuy Plateau]] and the [[Angara Plateau]]); and the [[Lena\u2013Vilyuy Lowland]].<ref name=\"Bridges\">{{cite book|title=World Geomorphology|author=Edwin Michael Bridges|chapter=Northern Asia|pages=124\u2013126|year=1990|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-28965-8}}</ref> [[Western Siberia]] is usually regarded as the Northwest Asia, [[Kazakhstan]] also sometimes included there. But Northwest Asia sometimes refers to [[Caucasus]] or nearby provinces.\n\n=== Geomorphology ===\n{{further|Geology of Russia|Geology of Asia}}\nThe geomorphology of Asia in general is imperfectly known, although the deposits and mountain ranges are well known.<ref name=\"Bridges\" />\n\nTo compensate for new [[sea floor]] having been created in the [[Siberian basin]], the whole of the [[Eurasian Plate|Asian Plate]] has pivoted about a point in the [[New Siberian Islands]], causing compression in the [[Verkhoyansk Range|Verkhoyansk mountains]], which were formed along the eastern margin of the Angara Shield by [[tectonic uplift]] during the [[Mesozoic|Mesozoic Era]]. There is a southern boundary to this across the northern margin of the [[Alps|Alpine]] folds of Afghanistan, India, Nepal, and Bhutan, which at the east of [[Brahmaputra]] turns to run south towards the [[Bay of Bengal]] along the line of the [[Naga hills]] and the [[Arakan Yoma]], continues around [[Indonesia]], and follows the edge of the [[continental shelf]] along the eastern seaboard of [[China]]. The [[Eurasian Plate]] and the [[North American Plate]] meet across the neck of [[Alaska]], following the line of the [[Aleutian Trench]], rather than meeting at the [[Bering Straits]].<ref name=\"Bridges\" />\n\nNorthern Asia is built around the Angara Shield, which lies between the [[Yenisey River]] and the [[Lena River]]. It developed from fragments of [[Laurasia]], whose rocks were mainly [[Precambrian]] crystalline rocks, [[gneiss]]es, and [[schist]]s, and [[Gondwana]]. These rocks can be found in the Angara Shield, the [[Inner Mongolian-Korean Shield]], the [[Ordes Shield]] and the [[Southeast Asia Shield]]. The fragments have been subject to [[orogenesis]] around their margins, giving a complex of plateaux and mountain ranges. One can find [[outcrop]]s of these rocks in unfolded sections of the Shields. Their presence has been confirmed below Mesozoic and later sediments.<ref name=\"Bridges\" />\n\nThere are three main periods of mountain building in Northern Asia, although it has occurred many times. The outer fold mountains, that are on the margins of the Shields and that only affected Asia north of the line of the [[Himalayas]], are attributed to the [[Caledonian orogeny|Caledonian]] and [[Variscan orogeny|Hercynian]] orogenies of the late [[Paleozoic|Palaeozoic Era]]. The Alpine orogeny caused extensive folding and faulting of Mesozoic and early [[Tertiary]] sediments from the [[Tethys Ocean|Tethys]] [[geosyncline]]. The Tibetan and Mongolian plateaux, and the structural basins of [[Tarim Basin|Tarim]], [[Qaidam]], and [[Junggar]], are delimited by major east\u2013west lithospheric faults that were probably the results of stresses caused by the impact of the [[Indian Plate]] against Laurasia. Erosion of the mountains caused by this orogeny has created a large amount of sediment, which has been transported southwards to produce the [[alluvial plain]]s of India, China, and Cambodia, and which has also been deposited in large amounts in the Tarim and [[Dzungarian Basin|Dzungarian]] basins.<ref name=\"Bridges\" />\n\n{{physical map of Siberia|width=200}}\nNorthern Asia was [[glaciation|glaciated]] in the [[Pleistocene]], but this played a less significant part in the geology of the area compared to the part that it played in [[North America]] and [[Europe]]. The Scandinavian ice sheet extended to the east of the Urals, covering the northern two thirds of the [[Ob Basin]] and extending onto the Angara Shield between the [[Yenisei River]] and the [[Lena River]]. There are legacies of mountain glaciation to be found on the east Siberian mountains, on the mountains of the [[Kamchatka Peninsula]], on the [[Altai Mountains|Altai]], on [[Tian Shan]], and on other small areas of mountains, [[ice cap]]s remain on the islands of [[Severnaya Zemlya]] and [[Novaya Zemlya]], and several [[Central Asia]]n mountains still have individual glaciers. North Asia itself has [[permafrost]], ranging in depths from 30 to 600 metres and covering an area of 9.6 million km\u00b2.<ref name=\"Bridges\" />\n\nSeveral of the mountainous regions are volcanic, with both the [[Koryak Mountains]] and the Kamchatka Peninsula having active [[volcano]]es. The [[Anadyr Plateau]] is formed from [[igneous rock]]s. The [[Mongolian Plateau]] has an area of [[basalt]]ic [[lava]]s and [[volcanic cone]]s.<ref name=\"Bridges\" />\n\nThe Angara Shield also underlies the lowlands of the [[Ob River]], but to the south and east in the Central Asian mountains and in the East Siberian mountains there are folded and faulted mountains of Lower Palaeozoic rocks.<ref name=\"Bridges\" />\n\n== Demographics ==\n{{further|Demographics of Siberia|Indigenous peoples of Siberia|Demographics of the Russian Far East}}\nMost estimates are that there are around 33 million [[Russian nationality law|Russian citizens]] living east of the [[Ural Mountains]], a widely recognized but informal geographical divide between Europe and Asia. The native [[Turkic peoples|Turkic]], [[Baltic Finnic peoples|Finnic]] and [[Tungusic peoples]] now are a minority in North Asia due to the [[Russification]] process during the last three centuries. Russian census records indicate they make up only an estimated 10% of the region's population with the [[Buryats]] numbering at 445,175, which makes them the largest ethnic minority group in Siberia. There are 443,852 [[Yakuts]] (Russian [[Demographics of Russia#Ethnic groups|Census of 2002]]) living in Russian Far East.<ref>[http://www.everyculture.com/Russia-Eurasia-China/Siberian-Germans-Orientation.html Siberian Germans]</ref> According to the 2002 census, there are 500,000 [[Siberian Tatars|Tatars in Siberia]], but 300,000 of them are [[Volga Tatars]] who settled in Siberia during periods of colonization.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20020227012304/http://newasp.omskreg.ru/hist/fotatlas/rezumeen.htm Siberian Tatars]</ref> Other ethnic groups that live in the region and make a significant portion are ethnic [[Volga Germans|Germans]] and they number about 400,000.\n\nIn 1875, Chambers reported the population of Northern Asia to be 8 million.<ref name=\"Chambers\" /> Between 1801 and 1914, an estimated 7 million settlers moved from [[European Russia]] to [[Siberia]], 85% during the quarter-century before [[World War I]].<ref>[https://www.jstor.org/pss/1848991 The Great Siberian Migration: Government and Peasant in Resettlement from Emancipation to the First World War]</ref>\n\n=== Urban centres ===\n\n{{Largest cities of North Asia}}\n\n== Administration ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Federal Subjects\n! Capital\n! Area<br />km<sup>2</sup>\n! Population<br />2010\n|-\n| [[File:Flag of Kurgan Oblast.svg|50px|border]] [[Kurgan Oblast]]\n| [[Kurgan, Kurgan Oblast|Kurgan]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|71,000\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|910,807\n|-\n| [[File:Flag of Sverdlovsk Oblast.svg|50px|border]] [[Sverdlovsk Oblast]]\n| [[Yekaterinburg]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|194,800\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|4,297,747\n|-\n| [[File:Flag of Tyumen Oblast.svg|50px|border]] [[Tyumen Oblast]]\n| [[Tyumen]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|143,520\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|3,395,755\n|-\n| [[File:Flag of Yugra.svg|50px|border]] [[Khanty-Mansi Autonomous Okrug|Khanty-Mansi Autonomous Okrug (Yugra)]]\n| [[Khanty-Mansiysk]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|534,800\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|1,532,243\n|-\n| [[File:Flag of Chelyabinsk Oblast.svg|50px|border]] [[Chelyabinsk Oblast]]\n| [[Chelyabinsk]]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|87,900\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|3,476,217\n|-\n| [[File:Flag of Yamal-Nenets Autonomous District.svg|50px|border]] [[Yamalo-Nenets Autonomous Okrug]]\n| [[Salekhard]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|750,300\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|522,904\n|- style=\"background: #DDD;\"\n| '''[[Ural Federal District]]'''\n| '''[[Yekaterinburg]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|1,818,500\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|12,080,526\n|-\n| [[File:Flag of Altai Republic.svg|50px|border]] [[Altai Republic]]\n| [[Gorno-Altaysk]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|92,900\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|206,168\n|-\n| [[File:Flag of Altai Krai.svg|50px|border]] [[Altai Krai]]\n| [[Barnaul]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|168,000\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|2,419,755\n|-\n| [[File:Flag of Irkutsk Oblast.svg|50px|border]] [[Irkutsk Oblast